## 1.11.1
  * `writing-migrations` now warns that the `log/report`/`log/info` calls
    it tells you to add will leak into Speclj output — a spec with dirty
    output is not passing even when assertions are green. Documents the
    fix: silence the migration spec with `(around [run] (log/capture-logs
    (run)))`, why raising the log level and `with-out-str` don't work, and
    the clj-kondo `around` gotchas (`:lint-as` entry + avoid an `it`
    binding name).

## 1.11.0
  * `writing-clojure-code` now applies to all Clojure code — CLJ, CLJC,
    and CLJS — not just backend handlers. The description was rescoped so
    the skill triggers on `.cljs` (defmethods, event handlers) where the
    same formatting and altitude rules apply; Reagent-component-specific
    conventions still live in `writing-reagent-components`.
  * Hardened the `cond` formatting rule into two explicit hard rules:
    every test and its result share one line (results column-aligned),
    and never put blank lines between clauses — a blank-line gutter means
    a result outgrew its line and must be extracted into a helper
    (even a single-use one). Applies to `case`/`condp` and to `cond`
    inside a `defmethod` or event handler.

## 1.10.0
  * Ship a baseline `cljfmt.edn` with the plugin and a
    `/clojure:setup-cljfmt` skill to pull it into a project. The config
    carries the Speclj / Reagent / c3kit `:extra-indents` the plugin's
    cljfmt-postedit hook needs so auto-format matches the documented
    style instead of cljfmt defaults. If a `cljfmt.edn` already exists,
    the skill shows a diff and asks whether to overwrite, skip, or merge.
  * `SessionStart` hook now suggests running `/clojure:setup-cljfmt`
    when a Clojure project has no cljfmt config (`cljfmt.edn`,
    `.cljfmt.edn`, or `.cljfmt`). Informational, folded into the existing
    toolchain notice — one message per session, no nag, no blocking.

## 1.9.1
  * Fix plugin install failure: wrap `hooks/hooks.json` contents in a
    top-level `"hooks"` object so it matches the current Claude Code
    plugin schema. Previously the loader reported
    `expected: record, path: ["hooks"], received: undefined` and
    refused to register the `SessionStart` toolchain check or the
    `cljfmt` PostToolUse hook.

## 1.9.0
  * New `PostToolUse` hook (`cljfmt-postedit.sh`) on Edit / Write / MultiEdit
    for `.clj` / `.cljs` / `.cljc` / `.edn` / `.bb`. Runs `cljfmt fix` on
    each touched file, then — if any file was actually rewritten — exits 2
    with a stderr notice listing the affected paths so Claude knows its
    stored content is stale and must Re-Read before the next Edit.
    Auto-format-with-notice (not check-only): keeps tokens out of having
    Claude re-emit the same code in canonical form, and keeps formatting
    decisions out of the chat transcript.
  * New `SessionStart` hook (`session-start-toolcheck.sh`). In a Clojure
    project (`deps.edn`, `project.clj`, `shadow-cljs.edn`, `build.boot`, or
    `bb.edn`), audits the tools the plugin's hooks rely on (`cljfmt`, `jq`)
    and emits a one-shot SessionStart `additionalContext` notice listing
    anything missing, with a `brew install` hint. Skipped in non-Clojure
    projects. Surfaces once per session — the PostToolUse hook itself
    stays silent on missing tools to avoid per-edit nag. Falls back to
    plain stderr text if `jq` itself is the missing tool.
  * Hook degrades to a silent no-op if `cljfmt` or `jq` is not installed.
    Real `cljfmt fix` errors (syntax error, parse failure) surface on
    stderr with exit 2 so Claude must address them before continuing.
  * Bash 3.2 compatible (macOS default). Sub-second on small files.
  * Install hint for users: `brew install cljfmt` (or download the
    standalone binary from https://github.com/weavejester/cljfmt/releases).

## 1.8.0
  * writing-clojure-code: new rule "Long cond branches → extract helpers". When a
    cond clause's result is a multi-line let, pull it into a named helper so each
    branch fits on one line and the cond reads as prose. Blank lines between
    clauses are a symptom that the clauses themselves became opaque.
  * writing-clojure-code: new rule "Long functions with stage/step comments →
    extract helpers; names replace comments". Section-labeling comments
    (`;; stage-1: fetch`, `;; manifest`) signal an over-long function whose
    sections want to be helper fns. Includes guidance on data-driven exit-code
    mapping and not duplicating cleanup across catch and finally.

## 1.7.1
  * writing-tests: clarify when to use `context`. Wrap 3+ related `it` blocks only;
    single-test or two-test groups belong directly under the `describe` with the
    var/behavior name embedded in the `it` string. Avoids nesting that adds no
    grouping value.

## 1.7.0
  * writing-tests: enforce one top-level `(describe ...)` per file with nested
    `(context ...)` blocks for grouping — multiple top-level describes are a defect.
    Adds a `grep -c "^(describe "` verification step.
  * writing-tests: new "Test Output Must Be Clean" section. Speclj output should be
    only green/red dots (or test names in verbose mode); stray println, log lines,
    stack traces, or reflection warnings count as failures even when assertions pass.
  * writing-tests: document `(c3kit.apron.log/capture-logs)` as the default mute for
    log output in specs, plus `log/captured-logs` for asserting on emitted messages.
    Preferred over rebinding `*err*` or redefining the logger.

## 1.6.0
  * writing-migrations: harden rule 5 (migration-scoped DB) with a concrete production
    failure mode and a test pattern. The "behind on migrations" framing was too narrow:
    a fresh DB is also behind every unrun migration, so any backfill that adds an
    attribute via the global `db/find` while the schema file already names a sibling
    attribute installed by a later migration crashes with :db.error/not-an-entity.
    Documents the real epic 2026-05 incident (webhook-secret + hmac-secret pair).
  * writing-migrations: reverse prior guidance that `db/tx*` and `m/add-attribute!`
    could stay global. Once a migration owns an `m-db` snapshot, ALL db-touching calls
    must go through it — `m/add-attribute!-`, `m/remove-attribute!-`,
    `(db/tx* @m-db ...)`, etc. Mixing global with scoped re-introduces the same legend
    pollution the snapshot exists to avoid (the global impl still has the future-attr
    legend).
  * writing-migrations: new subsection "Testing migrations that use a scoped DB" —
    `db/load-config` in tests returns the production config, not the lotr/beatles
    in-memory impl, so `@m-db` for real would point at the wrong DB. Override via
    `(around [it] (with-redefs [sut/m-db (delay @db/impl)] (it)))`.

## 1.5.0
  * writing-reagent-components: two new rules covering Reagent component API design.
    (1) Render subcomponents with brackets `[component]` rather than function calls
    `(component)`. Paren form looks harmless on stateless helpers (rendered DOM is
    identical), but breaks lifecycle binding (with-let/after-render fire in the
    parent's context), flattens ratom subscriptions into the parent's render scope
    (losing scoped re-renders), and costs React-level memoization. Also covers when
    keys are required (dynamic `map`/`for` sequences) vs. not (static siblings).
    (2) Pass hiccup children as positional args, not map keys. When a component
    wraps content, the options map holds only data (id, title, urls, callbacks) —
    children go as separate positional args, so callers read like hiccup instead
    of config blobs with hiccup nested inside. Covers fragments (`[:<>]`) for
    multi-sibling slots and trailing variadic (`& extras`) for optional content.

## 1.4.1
  * writing-migrations: extend rule 6 with a progress-logging pattern. Batched backfills
    on real data take minutes; without logs it's hard to tell whether the server is stuck
    or making progress, and a StackOverflow mid-backfill leaves no breadcrumb. New pattern:
    log/report at start/end of each phase with totals; log/info per batch with i/N.

## 1.4.0
  * writing-migrations: add batching rule for backfills. c3kit's or-where-clause builds
    :id IN queries via (reduce concat), producing a nested lazy concat that blows the
    stack on thousands of ids. Dev datasets don't hit this; staging/prod do. New rule:
    partition both the lookup and the tx* into batches (~100) when backfilling.

## 1.3.0
  * writing-migrations: reverse 1.2.0 guidance. Inlining the describe block in the migration
    file pulls test-only requires (beatles, speclj) into a namespace on the production
    classpath, crashing server startup. Put the spec in a sibling directory whose ns prefix
    is NOT :migration-ns (e.g., spec/clj/<project>/migration_specs/,
    <project>.migration-specs.*) so the migrator won't scan it and prod won't load it.

## 1.2.0
  * writing-migrations: document that migration tests must live IN the migration file itself
    (same namespace), not in a separate *-spec.clj file. The migrator scans migrations.* and
    calls up on every namespace it finds, so a separate spec file would crash startup. Tests
    in the migration file are discovered by speclj under the :migration tag.

## 1.1.0
  * Add writing-clojure-code skill: formatting (cond->, as->, continuation args, let alignment)
    and handler idioms (short-circuit with or, extract guard helpers, extract reusable predicates)

## 1.0.0
